<para xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="28" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p3.s1">
More general asymptotic formulas are given in Kaminski and Paris (1999).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="29" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p3.s2">
Just outside the cusp, that is, for <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p3.m1">x^{2}&gt;8|y|^{3}/27</Math> , there is a single row of zeros on each side.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="30" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p3.s3">
With <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p3.m2">n=0,1,2,\dots</Math> , they are located approximately at <Math equation-number="36.7.2" mode="display" xml:id="C36.S7.E2">x_{n}=\pm\left(\dfrac{8}{27}\right)^{1/2}|y_{n}|^{3/2}(1+\xi_{n}),y_{n}=-\left(\frac{3\pi(8n+5)}{9+8\xi_{n}}\right)^{1/2},</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p3.m3">\xi_{n}</Math> is the real solution of <Math equation-number="36.7.3" mode="display" xml:id="C36.S7.E3">\frac{3\pi(8n+5)}{9+8\xi_{n}}\xi_{n}^{3/2}=\dfrac{27}{16}\left(\dfrac{3}{2} \right)^{1/2}\left(\ln\left(\frac{1}{\xi_{n}}\right)+3\ln\left(\dfrac{3}{2} \right)\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p4">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="31" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p4.s1">
For a more extensive asymptotic analysis and further tabulations, seeKaminski and Paris (1999).
</sentence>

